# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asín-tibuok
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asín-tibuok/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:asín-tibuok/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:asín-tibuok/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:asín-tibuok/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaea-salt] It is claimed by one author that most alaea salt sold in the United States is produced in California, not in Hawaii.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaea-salt] True Hawaiian-made alaea salt is expensive and, before the rise of convenient Internet shopping, was difficult to find elsewhere.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaea-salt] Alaea salt gets its characteristic brick-red color from a volcanic Hawaiian clay called *ʻalaea*, which contains some 80 minerals and is rich in iron oxide.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaminos-longganisa] It is made with ground lean pork, ground pork fat, brown sugar, coarse salt, saltpeter, black pepper, bay leaf, vinegar, and garlic in hog casings.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaminos-longganisa] It is slightly sour, garlicky taste, typically bright yellow or orange due to the use of *achuete* seeds, made in bite-sized pieces.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is named after the Spanish “longaniza,” and is sometimes used interchangeably with the chorizo.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is a type of local sausage with two major types—the recado, with a more savory flavor, and the hamonado, with a sweet taste.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaminos-longganisa] Unlike other longganisa variants, the Alaminos longganisa's segments of the sausage are uniquely divided by small pieces of coconut leaf midribs (sometimes mistaken for toothpicks), making it easily identifiable.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaminos-longganisa] Each sausage string usually has six segments and is traditionally tied at the end with a length of buli palm fiber.
[src:asín-tibuok/alaminos-longganisa] The sausages are celebrated in an annual "Longganisa Festival" in Alaminos.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] The **Alberger process** is an industrial method of producing salt from rock salt.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] The Alberger process begins by heating brine under high pressure with a series of heaters.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] Impurities are removed using a tank filled with granite cubes called a graveler.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] When the pressure is released, salt crystals form in a steam-heated evaporation pan.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] This results in pyramid-shaped flake salt, which has low bulk density, high solubility, and good adhesion.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] Clair, Michigan that is the only place in the United States that manufactures such salt using the Alberger process.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] Diamond Crystal Kosher Salt is a brand of salt produced using the Alberger process.
[src:asín-tibuok/alberger-process] Because of its shape, density and flavor characteristics, it is often a preferred choice by snack food manufacturers.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The town is colloquially known as "Albur" for short.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Formerly, Alburquerque had one of the longest and heaviest pythons in captivity, with a length of 23 ft (7.0 m), weighing 620 lb (280 kg) and with a girth of 34 in (860 mm).
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] This female python died in 2013, but the mounted creature is still exhibited.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Since then, Segunto was changed to Alburquerque and its inhabitants are called *Alburanons* (*Alburquerqueños* in Spanish, Alburquerqueans in English).
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] In 1842, Lady Mariona Iraq asked for a chapel, convent and school to be built in Lo-oc.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The construction of these structures gave way to the establishment of Lo-oc as a barrio under the civil and religious jurisdiction of Baclayon and it was renamed Segunto after a town in Cataluña, Spain.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] In 1868, the town was renamed to Alburquerque.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Alburquerque is located in the western part of Bohol, 12 kilometres (7.5 mi) from Tagbilaran.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The town has a total land area of 2,865 ha (7,080 acres) which is relatively mild rolling to rolling and hilly.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The land is used as built-up area 216.5 ha (535 acres), agricultural purposes 2,511 ha (6,200 acres), timberland 15 ha (37 acres), mining/quarrying 44.3 ha (109 acres), roads 72.3 ha (179 acres), and landfill site 5 ha (12 acres).
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The central part of municipality, from the east extending toward northwest is characterized by rolling to moderately steep terrain (18-30% slope), with ground elevation ranging from 80 to 131 m (262 to 430 ft) amsl.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The area in northeastern and southwestern part is characterized by steep terrain (30–50% slope), with ground elevation up to 153 m (502 ft) amsl.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The southeastern part is characterized with undulating to rolling terrain (8–18% slope) with ground elevation up to 60 m (200 ft) amsl.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The area along the coast is characterized by level to nearly level terrain (0-3% slope), with ground elevation ranging from zero near the coast to 10 m (33 ft) amsl inland.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Alburquerque municipality is covered by hydrosol and three sorts of clay namely, faraon, bolinao and lugo clay.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The northern portion of municipality is covered mostly by lugo clay, the southern half portion is mostly covered by faraon and bolinao clay, while hydrosol has a very limited extent along the coast.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The municipal area is covered by grassland, coconut, shrubs and built-up area.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The northern portion is mostly covered with grass, with exception of small area in the northeast, which is covered with shrubs.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The southern portion along the coast is covered with coconut, with a small built-up area in the west.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The whole of Bohol is in Coronas climate type IV, characterized by rainfall evenly distributed over the year.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The average annual rainfall is estimated at 1,627 mm (64.1 in) per year.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The average annual rainfall is the sum of the average annual rainfall from respective river basin, multiplied with percentage of respective municipal area within respective river basin.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Several small rivers and creeks, which have their headwaters in the elevated terrain in the northern part, traverse the Alburquerque municipality.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] These rivers and creeks generally flow in a north to south direction and drain the major part of municipality into Bohol Sea.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The only major river basin is the Tagbuane River Basin situated on the eastern part of Alburquerque (19.94 km2 (7.70 sq mi) or 94.64% of municipal area).
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The municipality of Albuquerque has a poorly developed drainage system, due to presence of permeable limestone, which covers most of municipal area and enables infiltration of large portion of effective rainfall into underground.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] This is characteristic for karstified limestone terrain.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Surface water runoff (estimated at 304 mm/km2/yr (31.00 in/sq mi/yr)), is estimated to be 24,100 m3/yr (850,000 cu ft/yr) on average, which is sufficient to satisfy the water demand of 65 m3/day (2,300 cu ft/day) for irrigation purposes.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The potable water demand, including domestic, industrial, institutional and commercial water demands of urban and rural population, was estimated in 1998 to be 926 m3/day (32,700 cu ft/day), projected to increase to 1,529 m3/day (54,000 cu ft/day) by 2030.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Majority of this water demand (67.4%) in 2030 is for urban population.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The water demand estimated at 65 m3/day (2,300 cu ft/day), is required to irrigate 1.5 hectares (3.7 acres) of land in brgy Ponong.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Alburquerque is politically subdivided into 11 barangays.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Each barangay consists of puroks and some have sitios.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] There are 6 barangays which characterized as coastal (Bahi, San Agustin, Western Poblacion, Eastern Poblacion, Sta Felomina, and Tagbuane) and 5 as upland (Ponong, Toril, Basacdacu, Cantiguib and Dangay).
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Furthermore, the urban population is located in three barangays namely, East and West Poblacion and Ponong.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] At the 2004 census, Alburquerque had a total population of 11,489 people, with a population density of 320/km2 (830/sq mi) of land and an average population growth rate of 2.66% per annum.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The population increased to 11,246 in the 2020 census, with population density of 420/km2 (1,100/sq mi).
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Alburanons speak in Cebuano/Visayas dialect.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Alburquerque has an average annual income of Php 27,431,496.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The town has a labor force of 37% with an employment rate of 90%.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The average family income is Php 4,500/month with an average family expenditures of Php 4,000/month.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The town's major agricultural project is the "*Gintong Ani*" project in all barangays.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] One industry is situated in Eastern Poblacion - the Santisima Trinidad Ice Plant.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] There are 66 micro-type and 2 cottage-size registered business establishments with total combined investments of Php 1.5 million.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The existing tourists destinations are Sta Monica stone church and convent, Sta Fe beach resort, calamay making, ceramics making, salt making, loom weaving, basket and broom-making.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The potential attractions are Tarsiers Park, Lourdes Spring, Aquarium Fish, Butterfly Sanctuary.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Household weaving takes place in barangay Basacdacu.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Buri cloth is made from local young buri leaves for export to Cebu.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Midribs of the buri palm leaf are sold for basket making, and bundles of bure stems (pawa) to Tagbuane barangay for broom-making.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Several households use strips of older buri leaves to make spear-head-shaped fans 30 by 30 inches (760 by 760 mm) and smaller fans of 18 by 18 inches (460 by 460 mm) that they sell in Cebu.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] There are 50 households in the area making brooms from buri stems and bamboo poles.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Salt-making is another source of income for some Alburanons.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Production begins when the upland farmers plow their fields for rice production.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] This is because the "*asinderos*" salt-makers trade their salt for rice in a barter system, and salt production takes about as long as the growth of the rice it will be exchanged for.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The pottery-making enterprise is located beside the main road in East Poblacion.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Clay is dug from a pit near the sea, and mixed with silicate soil before being ground through the large rollers of an electric mill, in a pit beside the pottery works.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] This is mixed with water and molded into pots of various sizes and shapes on a potter's wheel.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The municipality of Alburquerque has natural wonders and micro local industries like the making of calamay, traditional method of manufacturing pottery, and the weaving of raffia using locally made loom.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The Municipal Marine Sanctuary, established in 2000 at brgy Sta Felomina where the beach and the Mangrove Protected Area are located, is set up in the area selected to be fit for the purpose due to its coral cover.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The sanctuary contributed to rising fish stocks and corals that had been destroyed by illegal fishers.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Bamboo rafts have been put in place to observe the marine ecology.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] It has been considered as a dive site of the municipality for local and foreign tourist visiting the place.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Other activities include trekking up to Tagbuane River passing through a Forestal Reserve Zone.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Some sources say the parish had its beginning as a *visita* in 1842 when a chapel was built under the direction of the parish priest of Baclayon.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The parish advocated to Santa Monica was canonically established on 18 June 1869, following royal approval given in November 1868.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] During the Spanish colonial era, the Augustinian Recollect friars administered the parish.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Up to the 1880s, the parish church was more like a huge shed.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Although it boasted three aisles, its walls were only of tabique.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The present church of coral stone was commenced shortly afterwards, utilizing the same three-aisled plan.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] However, the upper portions, especially the tower over the façade, were completed during the first half of this century.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] On examination it becomes clear that the link between the church and the *casa parroquial* was planned along a grander scale, but never finished.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The grotto at the back of the courtyard between the two structures hides a ruin which may be of another unfinished arcade.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Ray Francia signed the church's interior ceiling painting on one side of the choir loft.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Another section, now vanished, showed that the painting was carried out from 12 April to 3 August 1932.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] As regards the church bells, amongst them in the quadrangular tower are three bells, inscribed with the patron saints of the parish (Santa Monica, San Agustin, and "Calipay" or Joy).
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Dated 1866, two years before the ecclesiastical recognition of the parish, the bells are testimonies to the anxiety of the community in becoming an independent parish.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] As to the *casa parroquial*, the year **1876** is etched over the porta maior.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] However, in the center of the entrance arches to the steps, the year **1884** could be read until recently.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The church was severely damaged in the 2013 earthquake.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The power supply is currently distributed by the Bohol Electric Cooperative I (BOHECO I) which served a total of 1,281 households in the 11 barangays.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The main source of potable water supply is groundwater.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The total potable water demand of 1,070 cubic metres (280,000 US gal) per day.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The municipality has one local port situated in Western Poblacion, which serves local fishermen as well as other fishing vessels and cargo vessels in transporting equipment and raw materials from other neighboring provinces.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] It is fitted with proper lighting and equipment.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The municipal LGU as well as the barangay officials ensure the safety, peace and order situation and proper maintenance of the port.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] One of the biggest projects of the present administration is to provide its constituents with a sufficient potable water supply.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Almost 80% of the barangay in the municipality currently has water connections.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Ensuring quality education to the people is also one of the top concerns of the local officials.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The LGU assisted in determining and developing appropriate actions that would address the educational needs of the Alburanons in terms of budgetary allocations, maintenance of facilities and policies concerning education.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] Alburquerque has one public secondary school, San Roque High School.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] It has four elementary schools for intermediate level and three primary schools.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] It has also a total of 11 day care centers, one center in each barangay and one private pre-school.
[src:asín-tibuok/alburquerque-bohol] The number of teachers in the municipality is only 63 and the teacher student ratio in elementary is 1:24 and 1:43 in secondary level.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Both of them are part of the unique traditional methods of producing sea salt for culinary use among the Visayan people of the central Philippine islands.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They differ in taste from salt obtained through traditional drying beds or modern methods.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] *Asín tibuók* has a sharp, slightly alkaline taste with smoky and fruity undertones, while *túltul* has an innate savory flavor.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They are characteristically finely textured with small granules.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They are consumed by grating a light dusting over food.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The tradition of making *asín tibuók* and *túltul* is nearly extinct due to the difficulty and length of time it takes to manufacture them, the passing of the salt iodization (ASIN) law in 1995, as well as competition with modern imported salts.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They are only barely preserved in Bohol, Capiz, and Guimaras.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] *Asín tibuók* is listed in the Ark of Taste international catalogue of endangered heritage foods by the Slow Food organization.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Similar salt-making traditions also exist in Guimaras island and the neighboring province of Capiz in Panay Island.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] In Guimaras, it is known as *túltul* or *tul-tul*, meaning "lump"; while in Capiz, it is known as *dukdok*, meaning "pounded" or "pulverized".
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Both names are in the Hiligaynon language of the Ilonggo people.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The method of production varies slightly between the Boholano *asín tibuók* and the Ilonggo *túltul* or *dúkdok*.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Both methods can only be done for six months of the year, from December to May, due to the fluctuations in seawater salinity during the rainy seasons.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Boholano *asín tibuók* is made by soaking coconut husks for at least three months in special pits continually filled with seawater during the tides.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They are then cut into small pieces and dried for a few days.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They are burned in a pile until reduced completely to ash.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The ashes (called *gasang*) are gathered into a funnel-shaped bamboo filtering device.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Seawater is poured into the ash, allowing the water to leach out the salt from the ashes.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The brine (known as *tasik*) is collected into a hollowed-out coconut trunk beneath the funnels.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The *tasik* is poured into special clay pots and hung in walls in a special furnace.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] These are boiled for a few hours in the furnace, continually replenishing the pots with more *tasik* once some evaporate.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Eventually, the pots will crack, revealing the solidified mass of salt.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The salt mass will be initially very hot, and it usually takes a few hours before it is cool enough to be handled.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They are sold along with the broken domed pots which has given them the nickname "the dinosaur egg" in international markets due to their appearance.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Ilonggo *túltul*, *duldul*, or *dukdok* is made by gathering driftwood (*rorok* or *dagsa*) and other washed-up plant matter (twigs, reeds, coconut husks, bamboo stems, etc.) from the beach.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] These are burned completely into ash for about a week.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The ash is then gathered into cylindrical woven bamboo containers known as *kaing*.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The *kaing* are placed on bamboo platforms and a container is placed underneath.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Seawater is poured through the ash and caught on these containers.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The brine is then strained and transferred into other containers where it is mixed with *gatâ* (coconut milk).
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] These are poured into molds (*hurnohan*) and boiled over an outdoor stove (*kalán*).
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] More of the liquid is continually poured into the molds as they evaporate until nothing but a solid mass of salt remains.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] These brick-like lumps (known as *bareta*) are then packaged and sold.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Salt-makers (*asinderos*) were once important professions in Philippine society, but the craft is nearly extinct in modern times.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Part of this is due to the time-consuming traditional methods of producing salt and the hard work that goes with it.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Artisanal salt-makers can not compete with the cheap imported salt prevalent today in the Philippines.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] 8172, the Act for Salt Iodization Nationwide (ASIN), in 1995 also placed further stress on local salt-makers, forcing many to give up the industry altogether.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Both *asín tibuok* and *túltul* are only made by a few families today.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] They are commonly sold to tourists and to gourmet restaurants that feature Filipino cuisine.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Due to their rarity, they are more expensive than regular salt.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] Demand for *asín tibuok* and *túltul* frequently exceeds supply.
[src:asín-tibuok/asín-tibuok] The production of *asín tibuok* is also dependent on the availability of the raw materials, particularly coconut husks.
